Life Expectancy Analysis¶

Introduction¶

This is an exercise in both exploratory and explanatory data visualization. We have acquired two datasets on life expectancy (in years) that contain information by country, gender, income level, and more. This data was obtained from the World Health Organization (WHO).

Source: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/joebeachcapital/life-expectancy?select=WHOSIS_000001WHOSIS_000015WHOSIS_000002WHOSIS_000007.csv

In each section, we will explore the data and search for noteworthy trends. We will then generate visuals to display these trends in a clear, concise format.

Outline¶

Part 1. Life Expectancy and Income Levels

Part 2. Life Expectancy and Gender

Part 3a. Life Expectancy by Country: vs. Global Average

Part 3b. Life Expectancy by Country: Country Net Change

Data Recap¶

We have data for 4 different years: 2000, 2010, 2015, and 2019.

For each year we have life expectancy at birth and at age 60, by gender, and with health adjustment (by country or by income group).

HALE (Health Adjusted Life Expectancy) assumes full health, no injury or illness.

The different income groups are: High, Upper-middle, Lower-middle, Low, and Global.

Lastly, this data has no null values, and has correct data typing. No cleaning seems to be necessary, so we may begin our analysis.

Part 1: By Income¶

First, lets explore the effect of income on life expectancy, and look for trends between income groups over time.

Income Life Expectancy Gap¶

Upon closer inspection of these graphs, the gap between low and high income life expectancy at birth seems to be decreasing over time; meanwhile, the gap for life expectancy at 60 doesn't seem to be closing in the same manner. Let's calculate these differences.

In [ ]:
# Life Expectancy Change between Income Levels over Time, at Birth

years = [2000,2010,2015,2019]
incomes = ['Global', 'Low-income', 'Lower-middle-income', 'Upper-middle-income', 'High-income']

wealth_data_birth = pd.DataFrame(data={'Year': years})

for year in years:

        data = income_expectancy[income_expectancy['Year'] == year]

        high_income = data[data['World Bank income group'] == 'High-income']
        high_val = high_income['Life expectancy at birth (years)  Both sexes'].astype(float).iloc[0]
        
        low_income = data[data['World Bank income group'] == 'Low-income']
        low_val = low_income['Life expectancy at birth (years)  Both sexes'].astype(float).iloc[0]

        global_income = data[data['World Bank income group'] == 'Global']
        global_val = global_income['Life expectancy at birth (years)  Both sexes'].astype(float).iloc[0]

        wealth_factor = high_val - global_val
        poor_factor = low_val - global_val 
        total_spread = high_val - low_val
        
        wealth_data_birth.loc[wealth_data_birth['Year'] == year, 'wealth_factor'] = wealth_factor
        wealth_data_birth.loc[wealth_data_birth['Year'] == year, 'poor_factor'] = poor_factor
        wealth_data_birth.loc[wealth_data_birth['Year'] == year, 'total_spread'] = total_spread

Income Life Expectancy Gap is Decreasing¶

Based on these graphs, it seems that life expectancy disparity due to wealth has been decreasing for at Birth. For "at Age 60", life expectancy has essentially remained flat. Let's focus on life expectancy at birth, and generate different graphs that display our findings in a clear way.

        poor_factor = low_val - global_val 
        total_spread = high_val - low_val
        
        wealth_data_birth_male.loc[wealth_data_birth_male['Year'] == year, 'wealth_factor'] = wealth_factor
        wealth_data_birth_male.loc[wealth_data_birth_male['Year'] == year, 'poor_factor'] = poor_factor
        wealth_data_birth_male.loc[wealth_data_birth_male['Year'] == year, 'total_spread'] = total_spread


wealth_data_birth_female = pd.DataFrame(data={'Year': years})

for year in years:

        data = income_expectancy[income_expectancy['Year'] == year]

        high_income = data[data['World Bank income group'] == 'High-income']
        high_val = high_income['Life expectancy at birth (years)  Female'].astype(float).iloc[0]
        
        low_income = data[data['World Bank income group'] == 'Low-income']
        low_val = low_income['Life expectancy at birth (years)  Female'].astype(float).iloc[0]

        global_income = data[data['World Bank income group'] == 'Global']
        global_val = global_income['Life expectancy at birth (years)  Female'].astype(float).iloc[0]

        wealth_factor = high_val - global_val
        poor_factor = low_val - global_val 
        total_spread = high_val - low_val
        
        wealth_data_birth_female.loc[wealth_data_birth_female['Year'] == year, 'wealth_factor'] = wealth_factor
        wealth_data_birth_female.loc[wealth_data_birth_female['Year'] == year, 'poor_factor'] = poor_factor
        wealth_data_birth_female.loc[wealth_data_birth_female['Year'] == year, 'total_spread'] = total_spread

Gender Gap and Income Level¶

It seems that the gender gap in life expectancy is decreasing for high income groups; however, it is increasing for low income and global groups.

There doesn't seem to be a clear trend; even the movement we've observed is often very small. Let's graph each (at birth, at 60) for all 5 income groups and see if there is a clear trend. Perhaps the gender life expectancy gap is converging?

Gender Gap and Income - Conclusion¶

In conclusion, there doesn't seem to be any discernable or noteworthy trends with relation to the gender life expectancy gap. This gap has stayed roughly flat on average, and while it has made some small movements for specific income groups, there's nothing for us to further analyze. Women simply live longer than men, and this seems to remain true as time progresses.

Lets proceed to the next section of our analysis, where we will surely find some interesting results: life expectancy analysis by country.

Conclusion¶

This concludes our analysis of life expectancy from 2000 - 2020. We have sucessfully found and displayed the following results:

Life Expectancy Income Gap is Decreasing.

Life Expectancy Gender Gap has no Clear Global Trend.

Highest Life Expectancy Gender Gap is in Eastern Europe.

Lowest Life Expectancy Gender Gap is in Qatar (Males Outlive Females).

Largest (Positive) Net Change in Life Expectancy was in African Countries.

Smallest Net Change in Life Expectancy was in Caribbean Countries.

Top GDP Countries align with the Global Trends in Life Expectancy.
